The key insight in this problem is recognizing that the triangle formed by the two diagonals and one side of the hexagon is a 30-60-90 triangle. This is based on the properties of regular hexagons and isosceles triangles. By identifying the special right triangle, we can use the known ratios to determine the relationship between the shorter and longer diagonals without the need for complex calculations.
The two possible diagonal lengths are $AB$ and $AC$.  The measure of an interior angle of a regular hexagon is $180(6-2)/6=120$ degrees. Therefore, angle $BCA$ measures $120/2=60$ degrees.  Also, the base angles of the isosceles triangle with the marked 120-degree angle each measure $(180-120)/2=30$ degrees. This implies that $\angle CBA$ is a right angle, so triangle $ABC$ is a 30-60-90 triangle.  Therefore, the ratio of $AB$ to $AC$ is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}$. {{DGM:6a1fb85b4579f4a3}}
The ratio of the shorter diagonal length to the longer diagonal length in a regular hexagon is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}$.

The key insight in this problem is recognizing that the shortest path for each boy forms a quadrilateral that can be divided into two 30-60-90 triangles. By using the properties of these special triangles, we can calculate the distance traveled by each boy and then multiply it by the total number of boys to find the total distance traveled.
The thicker solid line in the diagram shows the shortest path that one person could travel.

\begin{center}
\begin{asy}
import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8)); dotfactor=4;
draw(unitcircle);
for(int i = 0; i <= 6; ++i){
dot(dir(60*i + 30));
}
draw(dir(30)--dir(90)--dir(150)--dir(270)--cycle);
draw(dir(90)--dir(270),dotted);
\end{asy}
\end{center}

The circle is equally divided into six 60-degree arcs, so the short distance (from one boy to an adjacent boy) is 40 feet, the same as the radius.

The dotted line is a diameter that separates the quadrilateral into two 30-60-90 triangles. In a 30-60-90 triangle, the longer leg is $\sqrt{3}$ times the shorter leg. So, the longer leg of each triangle is:

$\frac{80\sqrt{3}}{2} = 40\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$

Each person travels:

$40\sqrt{3} + 40 + 40 + 40\sqrt{3} = 80 + 80\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$

After all six people did this, the total distance traveled is:

$6(80 + 80\sqrt{3}) = 480 + 480\sqrt{3} \text{ feet}$
